{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647215"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18232"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18232"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.1,0.1,0.62,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10946"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73898"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10946"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59373"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7325"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26883"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73898"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe carpal tunnel is a narrow passageway located on the palmar side of the wrist. It is formed by the carpal bones and the flexor retinaculum. Several important structures pass through this tunnel.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is a content of the carpal tunnel?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ulnar nerve","Extensor digitorum tendons","Radial artery","Flexor digitorum profundus tendons","Palmaris longus tendon"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor digitorum profundus tendons\u003C/strong\u003E are one of the structures that pass through the carpal tunnel. The other contents include the flexor digitorum superficialis tendons, the flexor pollicis longus tendon, and the median nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E - This nerve passes outside the carpal tunnel, through Guyon\u0027s canal\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial artery\u003C/strong\u003E - This artery is located on the lateral side of the wrist and does not pass through the carpal tunnel\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor digitorum tendons\u003C/strong\u003E - These tendons are located on the dorsal side of the wrist, not within the carpal tunnel\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPalmaris longus tendon\u003C/strong\u003E - This tendon lies superficial to the flexor retinaculum and does not pass through the carpal tunnel\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The carpal tunnel contains the tendons of the flexor digitorum profundus, flexor digitorum superficialis, and flexor pollicis longus, as well as the median nerve.","The carpal tunnel is a narrow passageway on the palmar side of the wrist that protects the structures passing through it.","Compression of the median nerve within the carpal tunnel can lead to carpal tunnel syndrome."],"references":["Genova A, Dix O, Saefan A, Thakur M, Hassan A. Carpal Tunnel Syndrome: A Review of Literature. Cureus. 2020 Mar 19;12(3):e7333. doi: 10.7759/cureus.7333. PMID: 32313774; PMCID: PMC7164699.","Dincer, F., \u0026 Samut, G. (2014). Physical examination of the hand. In Hand function: A practical guide to assessment (pp. 23-40). New York, NY: Springer New York","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wojdyla, L., Hughes, T., \u0026 Stelitano, G. (2023). Hand Pathologies. In Textbook of Musculoskeletal Disorders (pp. 675-689). Cham: Springer International Publishing","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59373"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18232"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59373"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T07:50:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T07:51:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10946"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73898"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"htt